## Introduction to Data Validation



Data validation is the process of ensuring that the data is accurate and of good quality. It is an essential step, especially in the early stages of data collection, before the data is used otherwise; analysis of incorrect data will yield inaccurate results, i.e., garbage in = garbage out.



### ***Types of data validation***



There are many types of data validation. Most validation procedures will perform one or more checks to ensure that the data is correct before it is stored in the database.



Some commonly used validation checks are:



### 1. Data type check



Check whether the input data is of the correct type, i.e., numeric, characters, or special symbols



### 2. Code check



Check whether the input data is from a list of valid values or follows certain formatting rules, e.g., post codes.



### 3. Range check



Check whether the input  data falls within a pre-defined range, e.g., date, time, geographic data such as latitude and longitude, etc



### 4. Format check



Check whether the input  data follows a certain pre-defined range, e.g., date format: dd/mm/yyyy or yyyy-mm-yyyy, etc



### 5. Consistency check



Check whether the input data is logically consistent, e.g., chronological event: the delivery date of a parcel should be later than its shipping date.



### 6. Uniqueness check



Check whether the input data is unique, e.g., IDs, phone numbers, emails, etc



### 7. No null values check



Check whether the input data is not null, as some values cannot be null.



Every organization has its own unique rules for validating data. Performing data validation when the data is captured will ensure that your TPS contains valid data.



## A validation class



Data validation is implemented as a class with methods for performing various data checks following OOP principles.



In order to access the validation methods, an object of the class should be instantiated in the data capture GUI and the methods called from the object while passing the data to be validated as parameters.



