Notice the use of the Python built-in ***assert()*** function in the code in two groups of statements.



The ***assert function*** is used to check whether an ***expression*** is true or not



- For example “***assert (validation.is_numeric(10))***” checks whether 10 is numeric

- Since this is true, the assert statement is satisfied, and the next statement in the code is executed



If the condition is not true, an ***AssertionError*** will be raised, and the program will ***stop.*** When testing conditions that are not true, we use a ***not*** in the condition, as we don’t want the program to stop.



Thus, I have organised the assert statements into 2 groups to check the following conditions:



- those that are valid data and hence ***assert()*** should return True

- and those that are invalid and hence ***assert()*** should throw an ***AssertionError*** and stop the program. However, since I want the program to continue and execute the rest of the tests, I have reversed the returned value of the validation method using the ***not*** keyword.



Just defining a function does not mean that the code in the function will be executed; you need to make a function call to do that. This is done in the main section of the script, as shown highlighted below.



Also note that in the code, an object of class Validation is instantiated and passed as a parameter to the various test functions. This is because the test functions need that object to call its validation methods.



