This is my adaptation of the CRSIP-DM model.



Although the arrows depict the flow from one step to another, the sequence of the steps is not strict.



There may some moving back and forth between the different steps as this is always required.



1. Business Problem Definition



### **1. Business Problem Definition**



The first step, or phase, in the cycle is defining the problem. In the CRISP-DM model, it's called the business understanding phase.



**Type of problems**



Examples of business problems that can be solved with Machine Learning algorithms



- Detecting spam email

- Predicting fraudulent transactions

- Predicting whether a customer will be able to repay her/his loan

- Predicting whether a customer will leave the company (churn/attrition)

- Predicting health problems (diabetes, cancer, etc)



**Type of analytics**



Source: https://www.analyticsinsight.net/four-types-of-business-analytics-to-know/Links to an external site.



Machine learning can be used to perform 4 types of analysis (analytics)



- Descriptive – what happened

- Diagnostic – why it happened

- Predictive – what might happen (forecast)

- Prescriptive – recommendation based on forecast



Our focus in this module



- Descriptive (EDA)

- Predictive (Machine Learning)



**Problem formulation**



These business problems can be formulated as a binary classification problem



- Is the email spam or not?

- Is the transaction fraudulent or not?

- Will the customer leave or not?

- Does the patient have cancer or not



***Presence*** of the condition (spam, fraud, churn, cancer, etc) is ***labelled*** as 1 (or classified as ***class 1***)



***Absence*** of the condition (not spam, not fraud, not churn,  not cancer, etc) is labelled as 0 (***class 0***)



2. Data Collection



### **2. Data Collection**



The next step in the process is the collection of the data.



In many cases, the data might have already been collected and given to you as the data scientist.



