Handle outliers

The next data cleaning task is to handle outliers.



Outliers are unusual values that are far away from other data points. They might be genuine values, or they might be simply errors in the data collection. They are problematic for many statistical analyses since important findings may be missed or results may be distorted.



Unfortunately, there are no strict statistical rules for definitely identifying outliers. Finding outliers depends on knowledge in the area. However, there are guidelines and statistical tests for finding outliers.



a. What are outliers?

a. What are outliers?

If your variable is normally distributed, then outliers can be considered as those values less than 3 times the standard deviation below the mean or greater than 3 times the standard deviation above the mean. This is shown in the diagram below.



outliers-normal-distribution.png



However, many real-world datasets are not normally distributed. In such cases, the standard deviation cannot be used to identify outliers.  Instead, a box plot can be used. A box plot is shown below.



box-plot-outliers.png



A box plot shows the distribution of a variable in terms of percentiles. A box plot is also called a box and whisker plot.



A percentile is a certain percentage of values below that value. The 25th percentile is also called the first quartile or lower quartile or Q1. The 50th percentile is the median value. The 75th percentile is also called the third quartile, or upper quartile, or Q3.



The boundaries of the box represent the 25th and 75th percentiles. So, 50 percent of the values are inside the box.



The distance between Q1 and Q3 is called the Inter Quartile Range (IQR).



The line inside the box represents the median value.



The whiskers represent the minimum and maximum values. The whiskers are located at 1.5 times the IQR from Q1 and Q3.



A box plot displays a high-level summary of the data, that is, the minimum, the first quartile, the median, the third quartile, and the maximum.



Data located above and below the whiskers are considered as outliers; typically, 1- 5 times the IQR is used.



The upper and lower outliers are shown in the box plot shown above.



The diagram below shows the relationship between percentiles and standard deviations.



box-plot-std-dev.png



