c. Percentage outliers

c. Percentage outliers

Before we start replacing outliers, it's a good idea to determine the extent of outliers in individual columns (as we did for null values).



As mentioned before, if the variable is normally distributed, the standard deviation can be used to identify outliers.  A typical value used is 3 times the standard deviation away from the mean. Instead of using the standard deviation, the z-score can be used; it's the same thing as using the standard deviation.



A z-score is a numerical measurement that describes a value's relationship to the mean of a group of values. A z-score is measured in terms of standard deviations from the mean.  The formula is z =  (x - mean)/standard_deviation, where x is the value for which the z-score is being calculated.



The further away the z-score of an observation is from zero, the more unusual it is. Normally, observations more +/- 3 times the z-score are considered as outliers. However, if the variable is not normally distributed, we should not use the standard deviation or the z-score. Instead, we should use the values from the box plot. As explained before, any value less than 1.5 times the IQR from the first quartile or any value greater than 1.5 times the IQR from the third quartile is considered an outlier.



In the code below, as we did before, we set up a for loop to determine outliers for any number of columns in the data frame.



The first thing to do inside the loop is to calculate the values of the 25th and 75th percentiles for that particular column.  We need these values to calculate the IQR.



Next, we determine the length of the column as we need the total number of rows to calculate the percentage. It's always good to print stuff on the screen to know what your code is doing.



Next, we determine the number of outliers in the column. This is done by selecting, filtering, or indexing the data frame using a condition, as we did before. The condition is all the rows in the particular column with values less than the lower cut-off point or greater than the upper cut-off point.  This will return all the values meeting that condition.  However, we do not need the rows; all we need is a count of the rows. We can easily do this using the len() function. When applied to an array or data frame, it will return the length of the array, which is essentially the number of rows. We could also use shape to get the number of rows. Remember, shape returns a tuple and the first element is the number of rows.



Calculating the percentage of outliers is straightforward once you've got the count of rows containing outliers and the total number of rows in the column.



