The purpose of this learning activity is to learn about a number of  binary classification algorithms the purpose of which are to classify  an observation into one of 2 pre-defined categories.



### Binary classification modelling tasks



***Classification*** is a supervised machine learning algorithm  which ***categorise* observations** into ***classes***. The algorithm ***learns*** how to ***assign*** a ***class*** to ***observations*** that it has ***not seen before***. This process is called ***inferencing***.



In order to be able to do so, the algorithm has to be ***trained***. The algorithm is trained on ***labelled data***, that is observations with ***known classes***. Since the algorithm is trained on observations with known classes, it's called ***supervised learning***. There are also unsupervised learning algorithms - they use training data which is not labelled.



Classification is one of the most popular applications of machine learning. Examples of classification problems are: image recognition,



- speech recognition

- face detection

- handwriting recognition

- email classification

- cancer detection

- etc.



The list is endless.



If the ***number of classes*** to be classified in the problem is ***2***,  then it's a ***binary classification*** problem. Otherwise, it's a ***multi-class classification*** problem.



There are ***quite a number of binary classification algorithms*** in use. However, in this learning activity I've chosen to discuss 5 of them. I believe these ***5 algorithms*** will give you a good idea of the range of  available classification algorithms. They will give you a good foundation from which



you can build upon to explore other algorithms.



Since the purpose of this module is to give you an introduction to data science, I will not go deep into the theoretical foundations of the algorithms. The focus is more on the application side, that is,  what they can do to solve business problems  and how to use them.



Thus, I will still give you some very high level descriptions  of how these algorithms operate.



And, since we are looking at the practical side of things, I will also explain how to load the data and feed it to the algorithms.



