### 1. Logistic Regression



The first algorithm we are discussing is Logistic Regression. It is one of the most popular binary classification algorithms.



A logistic function is one that grows exponentially  generating an S-shaped or sigmoid curve. The output of the logistic function is a probability value.



The logistic function has lots of applications  and one of them is binary classification. And, if we are using the logistic function for classification problems, we need to convert probabilities to class predictions. This is done by specifying a ***cut-off*** or ***threshold*** point. Any probability less than the threshold is converted to class 0. And anything above, to class 1.



The threshold is normally set to 0.5 as probabilities are defined over the range 0 to 1. This is the default value and in the ***scikit-learn*** package it cannot be changed. If for some reason, you wish to change the default value,  this has been done by some external means.



So, in the figure shown below, for x values ranging from -4 to about 0, will generate a probability of 0 on the y axis. Since this probability is less than the threshold of 0.5, the output is 0. The class prediction will be zero as long as the probability is less than 0.5. And, if it's higher than 0.5, the class prediction is 1.



