Most machine learning algorithms need to be configured to get the best possible models. Configuration is done by means of special parameters. And in order to ***differentiate*** these parameters  from other parameters that the model learns during its training phase,  these ***parameters*** are called ***hyperparameters***.



The main purpose of the hyperparameters is to control the learning process. When you start the model building process,  you would use the default parameters to build an initial model. However, most initial models would not be good enough  and hence you will need to ***tune*** these hyperparameters.



There are various techniques to tune these hyperparameters. They will be discussed in a later learning activity.  And, not all hyperparamters need to be tuned. The hyperparameters for Logistic Regression are:



- Main hyperparameters

    - ***C***: float with a default value of 1.0, can be small number less than 1.0 or greater than 1.0



C is the inverse regularisation strength for the algorithm.  Smaller values of C specify stronger regularisation. that is, if you want to constrain the regression coefficients estimates  to close to zero or you want to shrink them,  use values less than 1.



- 

    - ***max_iter***: integer, default=100



max_iter specifies the maximum number of iterations for the solver to use. By default, this is set to 100 and is not enough for most problems. ***You will need to increase this value a lot for your assignment***.



- There are also a number of other parameters that you might want to tune, e.g. ***solver, class_weight, penalty,** etc. C*heck the model documention on sklearn's web site *at* https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression.htmlLinks to an external site.



