## Model building tasks



When building a classification model, we first build an ***initial model*** with default hyperparameters and evaluate it, then we try to improve this initial model by various means and select the ***best model*** based on appropriate metrics for the business case.



The initial model is also called the baseline model  as this is the model to which improved models will be compared.



## 1. Create and evaluate the initial model



Creating the initial model is a very easy and straightforward task as compared to data cleaning, EDA and data transformations tasks. Furthermore, you have already seen the code for creating the models in previous videos. And, you have also seen the metrics for evaluating the models.



One of the default hyperparameters for logistic regression is ***max_iter***. If you do not specify this hyperparameter, its value will be automatically set to 100. However, most of the time this value is not enough  and the algorithm will complain. So I had to set it to 200.



If you use one-hot encoding for one or more categorical variables,  this will add a lot of columns to your data. In this case, you may have to increase max_iter substantially to 1000 and even 2000 iterations.



It is also not necessary to specify the hyperparameter solver="***lbfgs***"  as this is the default value.



If you call the method ***get_params*** on any Sklearn algorithm,  it will display the values of all the hyperparameters used by the model.



So, the steps for creating an initial model are:



- Instantiate a model with default values and fit the model to the training data. The model is trained when the fit method is called.

- Use the model to make predictions on the ***test data*** and save the results to ***y_pred.*** We'll use y_pred later for evaluating the model.



### Evaluate baseline model



For evaluating classification models, we use a range of metrics. And the metric to use depends on a number of considerations.



One important consideration is whether the data sets are balanced or not, that is, are the number of observations for class 0 and class 1 more or less equal.



If they are equal,  you can use the ***accuracy score*** which is the percentage of correct predictions.



In many real world datasets, the data would be ***unbalanced*** or ***imbalanced*** as some people call it. In such cases, using an accuracy score would be misleading  as it does not represent the performance of the model. In such cases,  metrics such as: ***precision***, ***recall*** and ***f1 score*** could be more appropriate.



And, apart from using metrics with single values to define the performance of the classifier, a better way of evaluating a classifier is to look at its ***confusion matrix***.



## 2. Improve and evaluate the model



After having created the baseline model, you will need to improve it as baseline models are rarely good enough for production purposes. And, once you have improved your model,  you might want to further evaluate it against other optimised models  created using different algorithms.



In practice, you will not use a single algorithm to build a classification model. You will use a range of algorithms to build baseline models,



optimise them  and select the best one for production purposes.



There are several ways to improve a model.



Two categories of improvements are:



- data improvements

- model improvements.



Some examples of data improvements are:



- data cleaning, that is, handling missing values, outliers, etc

- feature selection, that is, reducing the number of features

- data transformations, that is, scaling, discretization, label encoding, one-hot encoding, etc



I've already shown you how to do all these. A fourth way to improve the data in case it is unbalanced, is to balance it.



Regarding model improvements, you can search for the best hyperparameters for the model. Please note that not all hyperparameters are equally important. Not all of them affect the performance of your mode.



There are several ways to search for the best hyperparameters.



- You could use trial-and-error and intuition or expertise to tune them. But, there is no guarantee of finding the best parameters when doing so.

- Another approach is to use grid search parameter tuning. This is an approach that will methodically build and evaluate a modelfor each combination of hyperparameters specified in a grid. Random search parameter tuning is another approach that will sample parameters from a random distribution for a certain number of iterations. A model is constructed and evaluated for each combination of the chosen parameters. Grid search is like a brute-force technique trying all possible conditions. If the grid used for searching is big, the search can be very time-consuming.

- A random search could be used but it is not guaranteed to find the best parameters.

- A promising approach for finding the best parameters is using the Bayesian optimisation algorithm. It is a global optimisation function that finds the minimum or maximum of an objective function.



I will show you how to used grid search for hyperparameter tuning later in this learning activity.



### Evaluate



Assuming that at this stage we assume that we have an improved model in the notebook. Our task now is to evaluate the model (in fact while you are searching for improved models, you would evaluate them  along the way).



So, you will need to compute the metrics for the new improved model. And in order to compute metrics, you need to use the model to make predictions on the test set. The ***metrics*** are ***computed*** using the ***actual classes*** in ***y_test*** and ***y_pred***.



