## Using a Jupyter notebook to optimize hyperparameters



I will now show you how to perform ***GridSearchCV*** using a ***Jupyter Notebook***.



GridSearchCV makes use of cross validation. The CV part stands for Cross Validation.



### What is cross validation?



It's a technique used in machine learning  in which the training data is ***split*** in several subsets called ***folds***.



In ***k-fold cross validation***, the training data is split into  ***k subset*** or ***folds***.



If ***k=5***, then **5 folds** are created.



The ***algorithm*** is ***trained*** on ***4 of the folds*** and ***tested*** on the ***remaining fold***.



The ***splitting process*** is ***repeated 5 times***,  with different subsets for training and testing.



Thus, when ***k=5***,  ***5 models*** are created and evaluated.



[](https://rmit.instructure.com/courses/161789/files/51635939/preview)



---



Source: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/cross_validation.htmlLinks to an external site.



---



For each split, model is trained and tested on different folds



- Split 1: model is trained on folds 2-5 and tested on fold 1

- Split 2: model is trained on folds 1, 3, 4, 5 and tested on fold 2

- etc



Each ***model evaluation*** generates a score  which can be averaged as a single score. This provides a more accurate measure of performance than  building and testing a single model on the whole training set.



When grid search is used in combination with cross validation, for each combination of hyperparameters,  k-fold models are built  and an average score is generated. Testing several models for a single combination of parameters is a more accurate measure of performance than testing a single model.



