## Techniques for handling unbalanced classes



### **What are unbalanced classes?**



This is a situation that occurs when the training data contains an ***unequal*** number of ***examples*** of the classes to be predicted.



There are various reasons why this unbalance or imbalance occurs, two of which are: the way the data was sampled and the number of positive cases that can be collected are limited.



If the training data is slightly unbalanced, this may not be a concern. However, if the imbalance is severe, then the predictions of the model will be ***biased*** towards the class that has many samples.



The class that has many samples is called the ***majority class,*** while the class with fewer samples is called the ***minority class***.



### **Methods for handling unbalanced classes**



- ***Resample the dataset***

    - ***Oversampling***: replicate observations from the minority class

    - ***Undersampling***: delete observations for the majority class

- ***Generate synthetic observations***

    - SMOTE: Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique

    - ***Create*** synthetic observations and add to the ***minority*** class

- Use Tree-based algorithms

    - e.g. Random Forests

- Use penalised versions of the same algorithms

